│ `select`s, etc.). For complex reasons, this attempt does not immediately commit and        │
│ returns, leaving the `vectorizer` object in a state where it has a plan for deletion but   │
│ hasn't executed it.\n3.  The pass then proceeds to call `vectorizeSimpleInstructions`,     │
│ passing it the *same* `vectorizer` object.\n4.  This second function calls                 │
│ `vectorizer->vectorize()` again for a new set of root instructions (the `sitofp`s). This   │
│ second attempt succeeds, modifies the IR, and *adds* its own instructions to the already   │
│ populated `DeadInstructions` list.\n5.  The core problem is that the `DeadInstructions`    │
│ list is not cleared between these two calls. It now contains a mix of instructions from    │
│ two different, and now inconsistent, vectorization plans. The second vectorization         │
│ modified the IR, invalidating the analysis and assumptions of the first plan.\n6.  When    │
│ the `vectorizer`'s destructor is finally called at the end of the pass, it iterates        │
│ through the combined, corrupted `DeadInstructions` list. It tries to delete instructions   │
│ from the first plan, but finds that some of them still have users because the second       │
│ vectorization has altered the IR. The `I->use_empty()` assertion correctly fires.\n\n###   │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n\nThe fix is to ensure that every call to `BoUpSLP::vectorize`  │
│ starts with a clean state. This makes each call an independent, atomic operation,          │
│ preventing state from one attempt from corrupting a subsequent one. This is achieved by    │
│ inserting code to clear the internal state-keeping lists at the very beginning of the      │
│ `BoUpSLP::vectorize` function.\n\n**File**:                                                │
│ `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp`\n\n**Location**: Insert at the beginning │
│ of the `BoUpSLP::vectorize` method, before line 4468.\n\n**Code to Insert**:\n```cpp\n     │
│ VectorizedInstructions.clear();\n  DeadInstructions.clear();\n```\n\nThis is represented   │
│ by an edit point that inserts code before line 4468.\n\n### 5. Conclusion\n\nThe bug is a  │
│ result of improper state management within the `BoUpSLP` class when it is reused for       │
│ multiple vectorization attempts. By clearing the internal instruction lists at the start   │
│ of each `vectorize` call, we ensure that each attempt is independent and operates on the   │
